{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519456","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519456"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:11:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:11:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13018"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13018","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13018"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.18,0.06,0.46,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5455"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48799"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5455","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5455"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13018"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33767"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1142"},{"type":"tags","id":"1820"},{"type":"tags","id":"2479"},{"type":"tags","id":"2701"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9255"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9558"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13293"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43378"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48799","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48799"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a five-day history of persistent, productive cough. He brings up clear to yellow sputum several times a day and has occasional shortness of breath and wheezing. He has found it more difficult to sleep in the last few days but does not have any associated muscle aches, fevers, chest pains, or chills. He has no history of smoking, asthma, or heart conditions but does experience seasonal hayfever which he manages with a steroid nasal spray.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his blood pressure is 130/80 mmHg, pulse 78/min, temperature 37.2 \u00b0C, respiratory rate 16/min, and SpO2 98% on room air. There is no respiratory distress, and the patient is breathing comfortably. Auscultation of the lungs reveals an occasional expiratory wheeze but no crackles or dullness to percussion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA chest X-ray shows normal expansion of the lungs without consolidation, and peak expiratory flow rate (PEFR) is 480 L/min (expected 550 L/min). A respiratory viral swab test returns positive for respiratory syncytial virus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Paracetamol","Oseltamivir","Azithromycin","Salbutamol","Ipratropium bromide"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has acute bronchitis. His symptoms are related to hyper-reactive airways and should resolve within a few weeks with supportive treatment. As he is having intermittent wheezing, \u003Cstrong\u003Esalbutamol\u003C/strong\u003E would be an appropriate management choice.  Salbutamol is a short-acting beta-agonist bronchodilator which relieves bronchospasm and its symptoms of wheezing and shortness of breath. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParacetamol\u003C/strong\u003E is a medication used to reduce fever and relieve pain. However, in this case, the patient does not have any symptoms of fever, muscle aches, or chills. His main concern is a persistent, productive cough, wheezing, and occasional shortness of breath. Since paracetamol does not address the respiratory symptoms or the underlying cause of the cough and wheezing, other management options would be more helpful.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOseltamivir\u003C/strong\u003E is an antiviral medication used to reduce the symptomatic period in cases of influenza A and B. This patient does not have influenza, and would therefore have no benefit from oseltamivir.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMacrolide antibiotics, such as \u003Cstrong\u003Eazithromycin\u003C/strong\u003E, may be prescribed for the treatment of respiratory infections, especially in cases of pertussis and mycoplasma. However, antibiotics are not recommended for uncomplicated cases of acute bronchitis as seen in this patient scenario. Acute bronchitis is most often associated with a respiratory viral trigger.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIpratropium bromide\u003C/strong\u003E is a short-acting muscarinic antagonist used in the management of chronic airways disease. It is used for management of exacerbations in chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), and as an adjuvant to salbutamol in managing severe asthma exacerbations, including in the paediatric population. This patient does not have underlying airways disease, and has no indication for ipratropium at this time.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Salbutamol can be used for symptomatic management in cases of uncomplicated acute bronchitis"],"references":["King D. Viral Infections and persistent cough: Evidence for treatment options. Australian Journal of General Practice. 2022: 51 (12). Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2022/december/viral-infections-and-persistent-cough","Becker LA, Hom J, Villasis-Keever M, van der Wouden JC. Beta2-agonists for acute cough or a clinical diagnosis of acute bronchitis. Cochrane Database Systenatic Review. 2015.  Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26333656/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33767"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13018"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33767","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33767"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-16T22:18:16+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-16T22:18:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5455"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48799"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7